%%TITLE
Cost-effectiveness of vaccinating the elderly and at-risk adults with the 23-valent pneumococcal polysaccharide vaccine or 13-valent pneumococcal conjugate vaccine in the UK.
%%ABSTRACT
The introduction of routine childhood vaccination with pneumococcal conjugate vaccines (PCVs) has led to a decrease in the overall incidence of pneumococcal disease in all ages and a change in the serotype distribution of the remaining disease. This study assessed the cost-effectiveness of vaccinating â‰¥65 years and at risk adults with either the 23-valent pneumococcal polysaccharide vaccine (PPV23) or the 13-valent conjugate vaccine (PCV13) in the UK, accounting for epidemiological changes.A population-based Markov model was used to track one UK-based cohort of individuals assuming PPV23, PCV13 or no vaccination until death.The ICER was estimated at Â£8413 when PPV23 was compared to no vaccination. PPV23 dominated PCV13.This model suggests that vaccinating with PPV23 is cost-effective when compared to both PCV13 and no vaccination. As PPV23 covers 80-90% in the UK of all serotypes causing invasive pneumococcal diseases, it remains cost-effective despite recent reductions in invasive pneumococcal diseases incidence in adults.
%%METHODS
Model structure
The model was adapted from a previously published cost- effectiveness analysis carried out in the German setting [3]. The Markov model tracked a cohort of adults aged 18 years or older, who were eligible for vaccination and who would receive vaccina- tion in 2012, from 2012 until death or 100 years of age.
Five health states were considered, following the natural course of pneumococcal infection –: no pneumococcal dis- ease, IPD, nonbacteremic pneumococcal pneumonia (NBPP), postmeningitis sequelae (PMS) and death . Individuals entered the model with no pneumococcal disease, and they were at risk of developing IPD or NBPP. Following recovery from the disease, patients would return to the state of no pneu- mococcal disease. A proportion of patients with meningitis could develop PMS. The model assumed that patients with PMS could not experience another episode of IPD or NBPP as the risk was calculated to be minimal [,. IPD and NBPP were associated with excess mortality.
The cycle length was 1 year in order to avoid complications arising from the seasonality of pneumococcal disease [. The model did not consider indirect protection of unvaccinated adults from vaccinated adults due to a lack of reliable evidence.
Target population & assessed strategies
The Department of Health recommends the vaccination in two groups of individuals: adults aged 65 years and older and ‘at-risk’ individuals aged 2 years and older, that is, those with conditions making them more susceptible to IPD or for whom that infec- tion would be more serious. The conditions include asplenia or dysfunction of the spleen, chronic pulmonary, cardiac, renal or hepatic disease, immunosuppression (asplenia or splenic dysfunc- tion, HIV infection, undergoing treatment with chemotherapy
or systemic steroids), those with cochlear implants or with cerebrospinal fluid leaks ]. As the number of children to be vaccinated was expected to be relatively low (1.9% of those aged between 5 and 18 years or 1.9% of the eligible popula- tion) [, the current model accounted only for adults aged 18 years or older.
The model compared vaccination with PPV23 against no vaccination or vaccina- tion with PCV13. The same target popu- lation was used for PCV13 so that the two vaccines could be assessed on a comparable basis.
In the UK, revaccination with PPV23 after 5 years is only recommended in those with asplenia (dysfunction of the spleen), chronic renal disease or those who have previously received PPV12/ 14 or PCV7 vaccines ]. The revaccina- tion rate was estimated using data
obtained from the Royal College of General Practitioners (RCGP) [SANOFI PASTEUR MSD, DATA ON FILE]. Between 2010 and 2012,
it was estimated that 5.0% of the vaccinated were revaccinated and that 68.0% were considered appropriately revaccinated (i.e., between 5 and 7 years following primary vaccination). In the model, it was therefore assumed that 3.4% of the vacci- nated received revaccination at 5 years. No revaccination was assumed for PCV13 as there is no recommendation for adults to date ].
Natural course of IPD & epidemiological trend
The change in the epidemiology of IPD, more specifically sero- type replacement, was considered in the model.
Before 2010, data were retrieved from the aforementioned HPA study ]. Figures were digitalized (GetData Graph Dig- itizer version 2.24, S. Federov, Moscow, Russia) where numeri- cal data were not reported and could not be obtained from the authors and health authorities. This study reported incidence of IPD associated with PCV7 or non-PCV7, for periods 2000– 2006 and 2008–2010. Consequently, additional information for the split between serotypes (i.e., included in PCV7, included in PCV13 not PCV7, included in not PCV13) was obtained from the HPA weekly reports on the number of IPD cases (digitalized) [.
From 2010 onward, PCV7 was replaced by PCV13 in the routine childhood vaccination program. In line with the effect of PCV7, it was assumed that the incidence of IPD associated with the additional six serotypes covered by PCV13 not PCV7 would decrease and that the incidence of IPD associated with serotypes not covered by PCV13 would increase in adults. In previous studies [, [SANOFI PASTEUR MSD, DATA ON FILE], it was assumed that proportional change in the incidence of IPD in adults was a function of cumulative vaccination rate in infants and children. A cumulative gamma distribution was selected
because of its goodness of fit. As no information was available for PCV13, the analysis assumed that the rate of change in incidence as a function of cumulative vaccination coverage in infants and children followed that of PCV7. The change was applied to those aged 65 years and older for whom statistically significant change was reported in the study carried out by the HPA ]. The change was assumed to last for a period of 4 years based on available data for PCV7, with a constant incidence rate thereafter. The incidence over time by age group is reported in . It should be noted that although PPV23 has been used in the past, no back calculation was carried out for the historical absolute incidence of IPD, therefore assuming no vaccination in the historical data. The approach was consid- ered as a limitation of the analysis. However, the approach was conservative since the total number of IPD cases had a down- wards bias, and hence the effectiveness of the vaccination had a downward bias.
In at-risk adults, the incidence of IPD was adjusted for risk group because the above incidence data were for all adults. The adjustment was based on another HPA publication by van Hoek and colleagues [, who reported odds ratio of developing IPD by condition and the number of individuals by condition. Esti- mates were not reported for those with cochlear implant or with cerebrospinal fluid leak and no excess risk was assumed, follow- ing a consultation with clinical experts. The proportion of patients in each risk group and the case-fatality rates by age group were also retrieved from the same publication.
The proportion of IPD cases involving meningitis was obtained from a study by Trotter and colleagues [, who reported the estimate (5.1%) for 2005/2006 in England and Wales based on HPA data. The probability of developing PMS (31.7%) was based on a meta-analysis of 63 studies involv- ing 3408 pneumococcal meningitis survivors in high-income countries [.
A sensitivity analysis tested the sce- nario in which NBPP was not considered.
Demography
Population size and life tables by age (2012 data) were retrieved from the Office for National Statistics [7,.
The split among those at normal risk, the at-risk immunocompetent and the at-risk immunosuppressed was based on the aforementioned HPA study by van Hoek and colleagues [. Individuals with chronic pulmonary, cardiac, renal and hepatic disease, diabetes, cochlear implant or cerebrospinal fluid leaks were consid- ered as the at-risk immunocompetent and those with immunosuppression as the at-risk immunosuppressed. How- ever, the publication did not take into account those on chemotherapy or on systemic use of steroids (i.e., immuno- suppression) due to the reporting format of the data, and therefore the size of the target population was under- estimated. This is recognized as a limitation of the study.
The proportion of eligible individu- als vaccinated was estimated from the latest data from the PPV Uptake Report published by the Department of Health [.

Vaccine effectiveness
For PPV23, vaccine effectiveness against IPD in the normal risk and at-risk immunocompetent was obtained from a Cochrane review of 10 clinical trials while for the at-risk immuno-
suppressed, the estimate was retrieved from a prospective trial in HIV-infected patients in the USA [1]. Vaccine effectiveness against NBPP in the normal risk and the at-risk immunocom-
dence of hospitalized noninvasive pneumococcal pneumonia observed in the two hospitals in greater Nottingham between 2008 and 2010. These estimates were then applied to the pro- portion of pneumonia patients hospitalized (32%), which was estimated as the midpoint of the range reported in the guide- lines by the British Thoracic Society [. No serotype replace- ment was considered for NBPP.
The case-fatality rate for hospitalized pneumonia was retrieved from the Bewick study (9.6%) [ and for nonhospitalized patients, 0% was assumed, following the British Thoracic Society guidelines [. The weighted average was therefore calculated at 3.1%.
petent was based on a Spanish cohort study that recruited 11,241 individuals aged 65 years and older between 2002 and 2005 [. No protection was assumed for the immunosup- pressed. The model applied the same effectiveness across ages due to a lack of information suggesting otherwise.
Due to a lack of information and an absence of head-to- head trials reporting relative effectiveness, it was assumed that PCV13 had the same effectiveness against vaccine-type IPD as PPV23 . Immunological properties of PPV23 have been compared to the conjugate vaccines in order to estimate their likely clinical efficacy in past studies. Such studies have failed to demonstrate the superiority of PCV13 in adults –.

In the model, vaccine effectiveness waned over time, with no protection being conferred 8 years after vaccination [.
Vaccine effectiveness against IPD was tested in a sensitivity analysis using the estimates from a recently published indirect cohort study conducted in England and Wales [. In addition, lower and higher effectiveness against IPD or NBPP was assumed for PPV23, while that of PCV13 was maintained.
Costs
In accordance with the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) guidelines, costs were estimated from the perspective of the UK National Health Service and Personal Social Services and discounted at 3.5% [. All costs were expressed in 2011 Pounds Sterling . Where necessary,
costs were inflated to 2011 using the Hospital and Community Health Services index [.
Based on the British National Formulary 63 (as of March 2012) [, one vial of PPV23 (Pneumovax® II, Sanofi Pasteur MSD) costs £8.32, whereas one vial of PCV13 (Prevenar 13®, Pfizer) costs £49.10. As neither of the vaccines are procured centrally, these prices were deemed to be a reasonably accurate reflection of the true costs to the health service. The adminis- tration cost was based on that used in an HPA study of the seasonal influenza vaccination program [5], which was 10 min of a band 7 advanced nurse’s time (£91 per hour of client con- tact, with qualification) [. The aforementioned RCGP dataset showed that between 2010 and 2012, among those aged 15 years and older, 18,970 received pneumococcal vaccinations
and for 10,313 it was co-administered with an influenza vac- cine [SANOFI PASTEUR MSD, DATA ON FILE]. The model therefore assumed that 54.4% of pneumococcal vaccination would incur no addi- tional administration cost. The average administration cost was thus calculated as a weighted average estimated at £6.92 for each pneumococcal vaccine administered.
The cost of an episode of IPD was estimated from Health- care Resource Group costs reported in the UK National Health Service Reference Costs , in line with a previously published cost-effectiveness study [. The cost of pneumococcal pneumo- nia was based on the weighted average cost of lobar, atypical or viral pneumonia (£1787; DZ11A, DZ11B and DZ11C) while the cost of pneumococcal meningitis was based on the weighted average cost of nervous system infections (£2573; AA22A and AA22B).
Cost of an episode of hospitalized NBPP was assumed to be equal to that of an episode of pneumococcal pneumonia (£1787). The cost of nonhospitalized NBPP was based on another previously published cost-effectiveness study in which levels of resource use associated with community-acquired pneumonia were collected from nine Medical Research Council General Practice Research Framework practices between 1999 and 2000 [. Unit prices were updated to 2011 [.
Levels of resource use associated with PMS were taken from a cost-effectiveness analysis of meningococcal vaccine in Eng- land and Wales [. It was assumed that 10% of patients
would be institutionalized on a full-time basis (£633 per week ) and that other patients would be managed in outpa- tient settings (£702.29 per year [). The annual cost was therefore estimated at £3934.96.
Effectiveness
Effectiveness was expressed in quality-adjusted life-years (QALYs), discounted at 3.5% [5] and weighted using the weights presented in .
Due to the lack of UK data, baseline QALY weights were retrieved from a US cost-effectiveness study that reported observed utility values by age group and risk group [2]. Com- pared with the utility norm in the UK (i.e., in healthy popula- tion) [, the US values were lower, therefore the approach was conservative. The health state utility value of IPD was based on the same study (0.20 for 34 days).
No decrement in quality of life was assumed for NBPP. The utility multiplier associated with PMS (0.6846) was estimated as the weighted average of hearing loss (0.8; 42% of cases) and other neurological sequelae (0.6; 58% of cases) [3,.
Economic analysis
The economic analysis compared vaccinating the target popula- tion with PPV23 with no vaccination or with PCV13. As per the guidance published by NICE, the primary cost-effectiveness threshold was set at £30,000 per QALY gained, with a
secondary cost-effectiveness threshold set at £20,000 per QALY gained [.
Deterministic sensitivity analyses (DSA) and a probabilistic sensitivity analysis (PSA) were conducted to explore the impact of the uncertainty around the model parameters. The range considered for each parameter was based on published literature or assumptions. The presence of epidemiological change was drawn randomly with a probability of 50% in the PSA. One thousand iterations were run for the PSA.
